rootNodes.name: Introduction to Trading Systems
rootNodes.config: { "title": "Trading Systems", "summary": "", "subTitle": "", "gif": "", "image": "trading-system", "definition": "Trading systems are the heart and soul of systematic trading, as they concentrate the biggest chunk of trading intelligence.", "paragraph1": "The rest of the infrastructure built into Superalgos—data mining and visualization, the trading bot and trading engine, the visual strategy designer and debugger—all have significant equity in the intelligence pie, but it's fair to argue that were developed to support the design, testing, and deployment of trading systems!", "callOut": "This tutorial will introduce you to how Superalgos views and handles trading systems. The rest of the turorials will teach you how to build them!", "paragraph2": "", "note": "", "tip": "", "important": "", "warning": "", "position": "Center", "slider": "toTop", "documentationURL": "" }

tutorialTopics.name: Frame It Flexibly!
tutorialTopics.config:
{
    "title": "",
    "summary": "",
    "subTitle": "Frame It Flexibly!",
    "gif": "",
    "image": "trading-system",
    "definition": "A ->Trading System-> governs trading strategies, and provides a flexible—but structured— framework to build them.",
    "paragraph1": "",
    "callOut": "Please, read this page to get up to speed with how trading systems work!",
    "paragraph2": "",
    "note": "",
    "tip": "There is no substitute for knowledge, so you will need to do some reading before I get your hands dirty with good ol' trading logic!",
    "important": "",
    "warning": "Skipping the reading may result in permanent neurological impairment. Your call!",
    "position": "Left",
    "slider": "toTop",
    "documentationURL": "https://docs.superalgos.org/suite-trading-systems.html"
}

tutorialSteps.name: Points To Take Home
tutorialSteps.config:
{
    "subTitle": "Points to Take Home...",
    "gif": "",
    "image": "trading-system",
    "definition": "There are some key learnings in the previous reading: multiple strategies, single positions, and precedence.",
    "bulletListIntro": "Let's take some mental notes for what comes next:",
    "bulletArray": [
        [
            "Multiple strategies",
            "may coexist within a trading system—as many as you wish."
        ],
        [
            "One active strategy",
            " with one open position at any given moment is allowed only."
        ],
        [
            "Precedence",
            " is given by the order in which strategies are defined around the ->Trading System-> node. You may change the order, of course!"
        ]
    ],
    "paragraph1": "",
    "callOut": "",
    "externalLink": [
        "",
        ""
    ],
    "paragraph2": "",
    "note": "You are probably asking why? Do these rules sound arbitrary? They are, for good reason!",
    "tip": "",
    "important": "",
    "warning": "",
    "position": "Left",
    "slider": "toTop",
    "pressButton": "",
    "documentationURL": ""
}

tutorialSteps.name: But... But... Why?
tutorialSteps.config:
{
    "subTitle": "But... But... Why?",
    "gif": "",
    "image": "trading-system",
    "definition": "Why would I want to have multiple strategies within a trading system, when only one of them may trade at any point?",
    "paragraph1": "Before answering the burning question, let's take a look at a couple of examples. Take a look at the two strategies within the Weak-hands Buster (WHB v2) trading system! ",
    "callOut": "Explore the definitions of the ->Trigger On Event-> on the ->Trigger Stage-> and see if you notice the difference between the two.",
    "externalLink": [
        "",
        ""
    ],
    "paragraph2": "",
    "note": "",
    "tip": "There's a hint in the name of each strategy!",
    "important": "",
    "warning": "",
    "position": "Left",
    "slider": "toTop",
    "pressButton": "",
    "positionAtReferenceParent": true,
    "documentationURL": ""
}

tutorialSteps.name: Steep Vs. Extreme
tutorialSteps.config:
{ 
    "subTitle": "Steep Vs. Extreme",
    "gif": "",
    "image": "condition",
    "definition": "Did you find the difference? Don't worry if you didn't! There are lots of conditions! I'll give you another hint!",
    "paragraph1": "",
    "callOut": "Look again and notice that the first seven conditions of the ->Trigger On Event-> are the same on both strategies! The remaining conditions are different, though!",
    "externalLink": ["", ""],
    "paragraph2": "",
    "note": "",
    "tip": "You may drag the ->Trigger On Event-> of a strategy and pin it closer to the event of the other strategy for easier comparison!",
    "important": "",
    "warning": "", 
    "position": "Left",
    "slider": "toTop",
    "pressButton": "",
    "documentationURL": "" 
   }

tutorialSteps.name: A Particular Case
tutorialSteps.config: { "subTitle": "A Particular Case...", "gif": "", "image": "trading-strategy", "definition": "Both strategies are virtually the same in that they share the same base rules for triggering... with minor differences...", "paragraph1": "Beyond the seven conditions in common, the Steep strategy has one additional ->Condition-> while the Xtreme strategy has three. We won't analyze those differences one by one, although you may if you wish! Let's instead reveal the underlying concept behind the differences:", "callOut": "Within the market ->Situation-> defined by the first seven conditions, the Steep strategy deals with a certain type of price action—price falling on a steep curve—while the Xtreme strategy deals with price falling on an extremely steep curve!", "externalLink": ["", ""], "paragraph2": "", "note": "", "tip": "", "important": "", "warning": "", "position": "Left", "slider": "toTop", "pressButton": "", "positionAtReferenceParent": true, "documentationURL": "" }

tutorialSteps.name: Another Example?
tutorialSteps.config: { "subTitle": "Another Example?", "gif": "", "image": "trading-system", "definition": "Let's take a look at another example! This is BB Top Bounce, a ->Trading System-> based on the bounce off the upper Bollinger Band trading idea.", "paragraph1": "", "callOut": "Expand the trading system node... Let's see what it may teach us!", "externalLink": ["", ""], "paragraph2": "", "note": "I told you! You may have as many strategies as you wish under the same trading system! Well... there your are!", "tip": "", "important": "", "warning": "", "position": "Left", "slider": "toTop", "pressButton": "", "positionAtReferenceParent": true, "documentationURL": "" }

tutorialSteps.name: At the Count of Three
tutorialSteps.config:
{ 
    "subTitle": "At The Count of Three!",
    "gif": "",
    "image": "condition",
    "definition": "BB Top Bounce features an interesting approach: it defines the trading idea with three simple conditions.",
    "paragraph1": "You are looking at the ->Trigger On Event-> of the first strategy. Notice the first three conditions defined...",
    "callOut": "Now go and look at the trigger on event of any of the other strategies... What do you see?",
    "externalLink": ["", ""],
    "paragraph2": "Eaxctly! All strategies feature the same first three conditions on the trigger on event. This shows that all strategies are based on the same trading idea. Now... how are they different?",
    "note": "",
    "tip": "",
    "important": "",
    "warning": "", 
    "position": "Left",
    "slider": "toTop",
    "pressButton": "",
    "positionAtReferenceParent": true,
    "documentationURL": ""
   }

tutorialSteps.name: Time Frame Analysis
tutorialSteps.config: { "subTitle": "Time Frame Analysys", "gif": "", "image": "time-frame", "definition": "Each strategy specializes in specific market conditions by analyzing the state of the market on different time frames!", "paragraph1": "", "callOut": "Take a look at the name of each strategy... 3H Down, 2H Down, 4H Up...", "externalLink": ["", ""], "paragraph2": "If you study the conditions that define the trigger on event, you will notice that 3H Down referes to the fact that the particular strategy is triggered when the 3-hour time frame is in a downwtrend.", "note": "Each of the strategies speciallizes on a certain time frame and trend!", "tip": "", "important": "", "warning": "", "position": "Left", "slider": "toTop", "pressButton": "", "positionAtReferenceParent": true, "documentationURL": "" }

tutorialSteps.name: Unpacking Lessons...
tutorialSteps.config:
{ 
    "subTitle": "Unpacking These Lessons",
    "gif": "",
    "image": "trading-system",
    "definition": "We've covered two examples of trading systems featuring multiple strategies... what can we learn from them?",
    "paragraph1": "In the case of Weak-hands Buster, each strategy represents a particular case of the same trading idea. In the case of BB Top Bounce, each strategy specializes in specific market conditions.",
    "callOut": "In the next few steps, we will unpack the implications of using multiple strategies within the same trading system and—finally—answer the burning question: why would we want to use such a setup?",
    "externalLink": ["", ""],
    "paragraph2": "",
    "note": "",
    "tip": "",
    "important": "",
    "warning": "", 
    "position": "",
    "slider": "toTop",
    "pressButton": "",
    "documentationURL": "" 
 }

tutorialSteps.name: Granularity
tutorialSteps.config: { "subTitle": "Granularity!", "gif": "", "image": "trading-system", "definition": "I mentioned the concept of granularity during the Welcome tutorial... remember?", "paragraph1": "Granularity is a device the helps in handling complexity. Instead of letting strategies grow into a complex web of rules and definitions, it is always preferable to split complex logic in pieces and deal with smaller units.", "callOut": "Splitting complex logic into multiple strategies helps in keeping strategies simple and understandable. It makes strategies easier to debug and to maintain!", "externalLink": ["", ""], "paragraph2": "Whenever you can, keep it simple!", "note": "", "tip": "", "important": "", "warning": "", "position": "", "slider": "toTop", "pressButton": "", "documentationURL": "" }

tutorialSteps.name: Hyper Specialization!
tutorialSteps.config:
{ 
    "subTitle": "Hyper Specialization!",
    "gif": "",
    "image": "trading-system",
    "definition": "Specialization is a very interesting concept that may lead to designing more efficient trading systems!",
    "paragraph1": "It is a well-known fact that most strategies perform better on certain market conditions.",
    "callOut": "Like with BB Top Bounce, a single trading system may feature multiple strategies, each specializing in specific trends, volatility ranges, or any other market parameter.",
    "externalLink": ["", ""],
    "paragraph2": "",
    "note": "",
    "tip": "Instead of designing a strategy to evaluate a range of market conditions, keep them focused!",
    "important": "",
    "warning": "", 
    "position": "",
    "slider": "toTop",
    "pressButton": "",
    "documentationURL": "" 
 }

tutorialSteps.name: Fine-grain Management
tutorialSteps.config: { "subTitle": "Fine-Grain Management!", "gif": "", "image": "trading-system", "definition": "When complex trading logic is split into multiple strategies, you gain the opportunity to manage the resulting trades differently!", "paragraph1": "We haven't yet got into how strategies are defined, but you do know that Superalgos allows managing the take profit and stop loss targets...", "callOut": "Each strategy in a trading system may have its own logic for managing positions!", "externalLink": ["", ""], "paragraph2": "If you handle multiple variations of the same logic for example, to take a position, then you will likely need to handle multiple variations for managing the position. It is easier and cleaner to do both on separate strategies.", "note": "", "tip": "", "important": "", "warning": "", "position": "", "slider": "toTop", "pressButton": "", "documentationURL": "" }

tutorialSteps.name: Going Long & Short
tutorialSteps.config:
{
    "subTitle": "Going Long & Short",
    "gif": "",
    "image": "trading-system",
    "definition": "We covered the three main reasons why it's a good idea to split complex logic into more than one strategy...",
    "bulletListIntro": "We also covered a couple of examples of trading systems doing just that. There is another example that comes to mind:",
    "bulletArray": [
        [
            "Going long and short:",
            " designing a strategy that goes both long and short is probably not a good idea. Split the logic and build one strategy for going long and another for going short!"
        ]
    ],
    "paragraph1": "",
    "callOut": "",
    "externalLink": [
        "",
        ""
    ],
    "paragraph2": "",
    "note": "",
    "tip": "Remember the KISS principle!",
    "important": "",
    "warning": "",
    "position": "",
    "slider": "toTop",
    "pressButton": "",
    "documentationURL": ""
}
